<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="424" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,258,1939]" pageId="3" pageNumber="424">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1482,1507]" pageId="3" pageNumber="424">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
New species can be easily distinguished from other species of the genus by upper margin of pronotum undulate, median carina high and lamellar before shoulders in profile and suddenly depressed behind shoulders. It also appears similarto 
<taxonomicName authority="Zheng, Wei &amp; Li, 2009" authorityName="Zheng, Wei &amp; Li" authorityYear="2009" box="[544,1115,1554,1579]" class="Insecta" family="Tetrigidae" genus="Macromotettix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="424" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="qinlingensis">
<emphasis box="[544,850,1555,1579]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="424">Macromotettix qinlingensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Zheng" box="[857,1115,1554,1579]" pageId="3" pageNumber="424" refString="Zheng, Z. M., Wei, X. J. &amp; Li, M. (2009) Five neW species of Tetrigoidea from China (Orthoptera). Journal of Huazhong Agricultural University, 28 (2), 141 - 147." type="journal article" year="2009">Zheng, Wei &amp; Li, 2009</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
but differs from the latter by lateral keels of prozona parallel (lateral keels of prozona constricted backwards in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zheng, Wei &amp; Li" authorityYear="2009" box="[1086,1260,1590,1614]" class="Insecta" family="Tetrigidae" genus="Macromotettix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="424" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="qinlingensis">
<emphasis box="[1086,1260,1590,1614]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="424">M. qinlingensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); upper margin of pronotum undulate, median carina high and lamellar before shoulders in profile and suddenly depressed behind shoulders (upper margin of pronotum slightly arcuate before shoulders and straight behind shoulders in profile in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zheng, Wei &amp; Li" authorityYear="2009" box="[151,323,1699,1723]" class="Insecta" family="Tetrigidae" genus="Macromotettix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="424" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="qinlingensis">
<emphasis box="[151,323,1699,1723]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="424">M. qinlingensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); width of midfemur 3–4 times width of visible part of tegmina (width of midfemur narrower than width of visible part of tegmina in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zheng, Wei &amp; Li" authorityYear="2009" box="[555,729,1734,1758]" class="Insecta" family="Tetrigidae" genus="Macromotettix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="424" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="qinlingensis">
<emphasis box="[555,729,1734,1758]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="424">M. qinlingensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); hind wings strongly reduced as strips, length of visible part shorter than length of tegmina and just reaching the base of hind femora (hind wings reaching middle of hind femora in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zheng, Wei &amp; Li" authorityYear="2009" box="[266,438,1806,1830]" class="Insecta" family="Tetrigidae" genus="Macromotettix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="424" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="qinlingensis">
<emphasis box="[266,438,1806,1830]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="424">M. qinlingensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="424" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,258,1939]" pageId="3" pageNumber="424">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1842,1867]" pageId="3" pageNumber="424">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from “ 
<emphasis box="[759,857,1843,1867]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="424">undulate</emphasis>
” and “ 
<emphasis box="[936,1015,1843,1867]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="424">femura</emphasis>
”, meaning lower margins of fore and middle femora distinctly undulate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
